            <div type="commentary" resp="#VM">
                <p>The inscription, mentioned by Camera (2010, 47, 115, in the publication of the excavations at the necropolis of Casa Cantoniera, Terravecchia di Grammichele) 
                    and published by Sudano (2105, 701, no. 1), bears a recurring name in the Sicilian context, Greek and non-Greek. 
                    See, in particular: the Sikel theonym Μαίη attested at Akrai (<ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/UQRFDXEG">Manganaro 1992</ref>, 474-485; 
                    <ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/4RHZUP7V">Manganaro 1981</ref>, 1069-1082); a defixio 
                    from Selinous that bears the anthroponym Μαίε (<ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/UGJNWEM5">Arena, ISAMG 4</ref>, 72-73). 
                    The name may occur at Montagna di Marzo on the bottom of a B2 Attic cup and a skyphos respectively (nos. 74-75, tomb East 31; 
                    <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic020740">ISic020740</ref> and <ref target="http://sicily.classics.ox.ac.uk/inscription/ISic020739">ISic020739</ref>). 
                    The reading of these two documents - μαιεσκακα and μαιεσκακα; αρ according to Manganaro (<ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/GRB3IPD5">Manganaro 1999</ref>, 19-27, figs. 36-37-38) 
                    - has, however, been questioned by Agostiniani (see more recently <ref target="http://zotero.org/groups/382445/items/RASC3AR5">Agostiniani, Albanese Procelli 2018</ref>, part. 186-187) 
                    who reads them as μαρεσκαμι and μαρεσκακα; αρ.</p>
            </div>
